schema: proofloop-spec-driven

context: |
  Project: <project-name>
  Domain: <project-domain>
  Product boundary: <product-boundary-description>
  Tech stack: <your-tech-stack>
  Documentation language: <e.g., Chinese/English>
  
  # ProofLoop 默认规范 (通常无需修改)
  Architecture: Layered rule-based governance over OpenSpec artifacts.
  Core roles: Brain (L0), Propose (L1), Executor (L1), Worker (L2), Verifiers (L2).
  State model: proposal -> specs -> design -> tasks -> apply -> archive.
  Canonical objects: change, spec, design, task, evidence.
  Authority order: openspec/ > AGENTS.md > tech-spec.md > PRD.md > CLARIFY.md.

rules:
  proposal:
    - Proposal is an intent snapshot. It must preserve Brain intent, scope, non-goals, acceptance criteria, risk posture, and minimum closed loop.
    - Proposal must not define implementation details as authoritative behavior contracts.

  specs:
    - Specs are the behavior contract source of truth.
    - Binding behavior that affects observable runtime behavior, API contracts, event delivery, persistence, failure semantics, or user-visible outcomes MUST appear in specs.
    - Specs must not contain internal implementation plans unless they are externally observable requirements.
    - Spec directory name must match kebab-case: start with lowercase letter, contain only lowercase letters, digits, and hyphens.
    - Forbidden: leading digit, version suffix (-bN/-vN), fix-/remediation-/visible- prefix.
    - Forbidden: stage-N- prefix — stage markers belong in change names, not spec names.
    - Before creating a new spec, check if base specs already contain a spec for the same capability. If so, use `## ADDED Requirements / ## MODIFIED Requirements` to extend rather than creating a duplicate.

  design:
    - Design is technical rationale for implementing specs.
    - Each binding decision must state whether it is behavior-binding or implementation-only.
    - Behavior-binding decisions must reference source spec requirements.
    - Implementation-only decisions may project to tasks but must not redefine behavior contracts.

  tasks:
    - Tasks are executable projections of specs and design.
    - Each implementation slice must reference source spec requirements.
    - Each Slice Contract must be self-contained enough for Executor to build Worker Dispatch Packet.
    - Tasks must not introduce behavior not present in specs.
    - Tasks must include verification method, expected evidence, allowed scope, stop conditions, and verifier gate for each implementation slice.
    - Tasks must include dependencies and parallel opportunities.
    - "`[P]` marks a parallel candidate, not mandatory parallel execution."
